        <body>

            <pb n="1"/>

            <p>Rev &#38; dear Sir&#58;</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Yours from yesterday came<lb/> duly on hand&#44; and in reply to the same<lb/> I have
                to state that in regard of <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Yechiel Hakohen</persName> I have
                send a letter al&#8211;<lb/>ready to <persName>Jos M. Ash</persName>&#44; Esq.
                viz<lb/>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">That he must not accept the evil<lb/> report at all&#44; nor any portion of it.
                The<lb/> report which I have heard was about <persName>Mosca<lb/>
                Suzi</persName>Mosca<lb/> Suzi&#44; a Meshulach&#42; according to his own<lb/>
                statement. <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName> said that it is true<lb/> that he was
                a Meshulach sometime ago but is<lb/> that no longer. The above named <persName>Rabbi
                    Moses</persName>&#44;<lb/> however showed me a letter from one of the men<lb/>
                of <placeName><hi rend="underline">Susa</hi></placeName>&#44; whom he met here in a
                city in the South&#44; to<lb/> the effect that <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName> is
                now here having<lb/> relations with one of the women of this land. I don&#39;t
                know<lb/> who is correct&#44; but in any event I have no doubt<lb/> that this man
                told a lie. For&#44; as I have hear<add>d</add><lb/> from <persName>Mr. Sim
                    Abraham</persName>&#44; who had been in
                <placeName>Jeru<lb/>salem</placeName>&#44; this is what he said about this
                    <persName>Rabbi Yechiel</persName></p>

            <p>&#42; a man sent from <placeName>Palestine</placeName> or from Yeshivah to <del>get the</del>
                collect<lb/> money./</p>

            <pb n="2"/>
            <p><add>&#63;</add><lb/> about 1900&#44; and when the inhabitants of<lb/>
                <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName> were told of this they sent after<lb/> him and
                insisted that he go again to<lb/>
                <placeName>America</placeName> and they made some arrangements<lb/> with him
                &#40;but I don&#39;t know whether <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Abraham</persName> knows
                anything&#41;. The agreement<lb/> was that he should collect money for the<lb/>
                building of a synagogue or a Beth Midrash&#44;<lb/> and <del>they met</del> his recommendations
                are all<lb/> flattering. The impression one gets is that<lb/> they are true. That is
                why I cannot<lb/> agree to these words&#44; which may be the<lb/> result of an
                &#8220;agreement&#8221; between <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Moses</persName> and the man
                from <placeName>Susa</placeName> because <persName>Rabbi<lb/> Yechiel</persName>
                said something&#44; whether true or false&#44;<lb/> about <persName>Rabbi
                    Moses</persName>. Therefore I advise<lb/> you not to pay any attention to
                this<lb/> matter&#44; lest&#44; God forbid&#44; there grow out of<lb/> this matter a
                profanation of God&#39;s name&#44;<lb/> <del>if some</del> there be truth in the matter. God
                knows<lb/> the hidden secrets of the heart and He<lb/> proves the reins and the
                heart and<lb/> nothing is hidden from him.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Whoever judges his friend leniently</p>

            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>may God come to his aid and grant<lb/> him length of days. May he leave when<lb/> the
                scattered remnants of <placeName>Israel</placeName> are<lb/> gathered together and
                    <placeName>Zion</placeName> is renewed<lb/> and <placeName>Jerusalem</placeName>
                is rebuilt Amen.<lb/> May that be God&#39;s will. From me who<lb/> writes with a
                broken heart.<lb/>
                <persName role="author">Simon Noht</persName>.</p>

        </body>
